Europe
--------
[1] Russian Federation
Date: Fri 17 Jan 2014
Source: Rospotrebnadzor, Advisory Council on Consumer Protection (CPS), Press Release [in Russian, trans. Mod.CP, edited]
http://tinyurl.com/pfv7hqj


In the Russian Federation, as well as in the European region generally, measles continues to be a serious problem. According to the World Health Organization, in 2013 in 37 European countries, there were more than 26 000 cases of measles infection. By the end of the year, a worsening situation in Turkey and Indonesia -- countries which traditionally have been visited by Russian tourists -- had repercussions in the Russian Federation. Cases of measles were also imported from Thailand to Russia and China.

In the Russian Federation during 2013, cases of measles were reported in 58 regions. About 45 percent of the cases were children, mostly unvaccinated individuals. Group outbreaks of measles were recorded in a number of educational institutions, including a medical institution in the Astrakhan Region. In the Republic of Dagestan, measles outbreaks have been reported among unvaccinated migrant Roma communities in the Ryazan, Yaroslavl, Tula, Kaluga, Orenburg, Saratov, and Nizhny Novgorod regions, and also in the Republics of Bashkortostan and Adygea in the Stavropol Territory. Currently, a large outbreak of measles with over 90 victims has been recorded in the Kursk Region among members of a community who refuse preventive vaccinations on religious grounds.

Measles is one of the most contagious viral infections that is spread from person to person. Transmission is carried by droplets. Dangerous potential complications may follow infection, affecting the central nervous system, respiratory system, and gastrointestinal tract. Measles can be a cause of death and disability, especially among young children.

Persons who have not experienced measles virus infection and who have not been vaccinated against it are highly susceptible to the disease throughout life and can contract measles at any age. The most effective measure to prevent measles is immunisation. The CPS recommends vaccination for all children and adults with no record of prior immunisation against this disease according to the National Calendar of Preventive Vaccinations. This is especially true for those who regularly travel to medically underdeveloped countries. Parents who refuse vaccination endanger the health and lives of their children.

