[2] UK (Devon)
Date: Sat 24 Jan 2014
Source: Herald Express [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.torquayheraldexpress.co.uk/Warning-parents-following-confirmed-case-measles/story-20499944-detail/story.html


Public Health England (PHE) confirmed it was working with Torbay Council following a confirmed case of measles in a child in the area.

The affected child has now fully recovered and returned to school. Letters with information provided by PHE have been sent to parents advising them to ensure that their children are adequately immunised. To confer protection, children should have had 2 doses of MMR, the immunisation that protects against measles, mumps, and rubella as part of the National Childhood Immunisation Programme.

The rest of the school have also been given advice on signs and symptoms of measles, which include fever, cough, red and painful eyes, cold-like symptoms, loss of appetite, and rash which tends to follow 3 to 4 days after the onset of the other symptoms.

Mike Wade, consultant in public health at the regional PHE Centre, said: "Measles is a very infectious virus, and can spread rapidly in close-knit communities such as schools if people have not been immunised. While most people who catch measles will recover completely within a couple of weeks, it's important to remember measles can be a very serious illness that can leave permanent disability, and occasionally even kill."

Caroline Dimond, director of public health for Torbay, said: "Although the incidence of measles across Torbay is low, in order to prevent a measles outbreak, it is really important that parents of children, particularly between the ages of 10 and 16, who have not been immunised or had the 2nd MMR jab contact their GP surgery to arrange a vaccination."

