[3] UK (Wales)
Date: Thu 23 Jan 2014
Source: Wales Online [edited]
http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/new-cases-measles-cases-reported-6556362


Parents are being urged to make sure their children are fully vaccinated against measles following a rise in the number of cases of the virus [disease] in South West Wales. Public Health Wales said that, as at the end of December 2013, there had been 44 cases in the outbreak, 1st reported as being linked to 4 schools in the Neath and Swansea area. Another 5 new cases have been reported locally in the last 11 days, although Public Health Wales says these cannot be directly linked to the outbreak.

The new cases are mainly around the Swansea and Neath area, but there have been cases in Carmarthenshire, with one person requiring hospital treatment. Public Health Wales said that children between 10-18 have mainly been affected by the outbreak, but a number of adults, who are more likely to suffer complications of the infection, have also been diagnosed with the potentially fatal virus.

Dr Jorg Hoffmann, consultant in communicable disease control for Public Health Wales, said: "It is really disappointing to see more cases of measles in the Swansea and Neath area, and we continue to remind everyone of the importance of MMR vaccination. It is very concerning that this outbreak is continuing to spread. This is a potentially nasty infection that can easily be prevented with a safe, effective vaccine, and we would not see measles in Wales if enough children and young people were vaccinated. Uptake of the MMR vaccine in small children is the highest it has ever been in Wales, but we still have a large number of children and teenagers aged 10 to 18 who are not vaccinated. We are also seeing adult cases and would urge anyone born after 1970 to check whether they have either had measles or 2 doses of the MMR vaccination and speak to their GP urgently if they have not. This age group is most vulnerable to the complications of measles. It simply is not worth the risk for anyone of any age to remain unvaccinated."

The current outbreak follows the largest ever outbreak of measles in Wales since the introduction of the MMR vaccination, with more than 1200 cases of measles in the same area between November 2012 and July 2013. In that outbreak, 88 people were hospitalised and one adult died.

Although more than 70 000 catch up doses of MMR were given across Wales during the last outbreak, around 30 000 children and young people in the 10 to 18 age group remain unprotected.

Dr Hoffmann said: "To try to bring the outbreak linked to 4 schools in the Neath and Swansea area under control, schools were advised to ask unvaccinated children who were close contacts of measles cases to stay away from school. We know that many of these children went on to develop measles and that keeping them away from school helped stop the outbreak from spreading further. We would advise parents that if their children are not vaccinated and come into contact with people with measles, they may not be able to attend school until the risk has passed, so it makes best sense to vaccinate them as soon as possible."

