[9] Canada (Saskatchewan)
Date: Fri 24 Jan 2014
Source: News Talk 980, CJME [edited]
http://cjme.com/story/overview-reginas-measles-situation-so-far/233033


So far, 5 people are in quarantine after contracting the red measles [as opposed to German] virus, and the Ministry of Health has been busy tracing their steps to keep it from spreading.

The virus is well known across the globe, but according to chief medical health officer Dr. Saqib Shahab, it's not seen in Canada very often. Usually, he said, it is transferred here through travel. In this case, 2 people brought the virus into Regina from overseas.

"In one particular instance, there was no further [transmission] of measles. In the 2nd instance, after the initial case, which presented in the 1st week of January 2014, there have been a further 3 cases that are linked to that initial case," said Shahab. He said none of those additional 3 people were family members of the initial carrier, but he said they were in the same room as that person at some point.

"Even one or 2 (cases) for us would be a concern, because those people could expose others," he said. "The concern, obviously, is that if half of the people in a room weren't vaccinated, then you know you could see several dozen cases. I think the good news in Saskatchewan is that our overall immunization rates are high. In Saskatchewan, 90 per cent of the population is fully vaccinated."

According to Shahab, anyone born prior to 1970 is considered to be immune. Anyone born after that who has had 2 MMR (measles, mumps, and rubella) shots would also be considered to be immune. Those left would only be at risk if they had been in a small room with an individual who was infected.

This is why the Ministry of Health has been tracking where those 5 people went before being put into quarantine. A list of the places and times that people may have come into contact with the virus is listed below:

- Hotel Saskatchewan Radisson Plaza (19 Jan 2014 between 9:30 and 1:30 p.m.)
- Superstore, Rochdale area (17 Jan 2014 between 11 a.m. and 1:30 p.m.)
- Wal-Mart, Rochdale area (17 Jan 2014 between 11:15 a.m. and 1:45 p.m.)
- Uplands Pizza (17 Jan 2014 between 11:45 a.m. and 3 p.m.)
- Co-Operators Centre at Evraz Place (18 Jan 2014 between 1:30 p.m. and 5:45 p.m.)
- Soma Salon and Spa (20 Jan 2014 between 3:15 p.m. and 6:30 p.m.)
- Security Building Supplies (13-17 Jan 2014)
- Chapters/Starbucks (13 Jan 2014 between 10 a.m. and 1:30 p.m. and 22 Jan 2014 between 9:30 and 1:15 a.m.)
- Sobeys, south Albert St. (13 Jan 2014 between 10 a.m. and 1 p.m.)
- Lawson Aquatic Centre (14 Jan 2014 between 12:30 and 5:30 p.m.)
- Safeway, Cathedral area (14 Jan 2014 between 3:30 and 6:30 p.m.)
- Menchie's Frozen Yogurt, east end (14 Jan 2014 between 8 and 11 p.m.)
- Argyle Park Community Centre (14 Jan 2014 between 6:30 and 9 p.m. and 15 Jan 2014 between 6:30 and 9 p.m.)
- Uplands Community Centre (14 Jan 2014 between 6:30 and 9 p.m.)

Shahab said measles symptoms typically are red eyes, fever, cough, and a runny nose followed by a rash. He said it can take up to 3 weeks for those symptoms to develop after the onset of the infection.

[Byline: Aaron Stuckel]

