[11] Australia (Queensland)
Date: Sun 26 Jan 2014
Source: Brisbane Times [edited]
http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/another-measles-case-in-brisbane-20140126-31grc.html


Recent travellers between the Philippines and Sydney and Sydney to Brisbane have been urged to be on alert for measles symptoms.

A man from Brisbane's south side has been diagnosed with the highly contagious disease, and Queensland Health officials have warned that he was likely to have been contagious when he flew on Qantas from the Philippines to Sydney and then continued on a domestic leg back to Brisbane on 21 Jan 2014.

Anyone who may have visited the IGA at Carina on 22 Jan 2014 could also be at risk of contracting measles.

Metro South Hospital and Health Service staff will be contacting people known to have interacted with the man, but public health physician Brad McCall said that given the large number of people potentially at risk, the public also needed to be vigilant. "If people are adequately vaccinated with 2 recorded doses of measles, mumps, rubella (MMR) vaccine, they are very unlikely to get the disease," Dr McCall said. "Measles is one of the most infectious of all communicable diseases and is spread by tiny droplets through coughing and sneezing. Symptoms usually start around 10 days after infection, but sometimes longer, so anyone who develops measles-like symptoms within the next week should contact their GP for advice. It is very important to call the medical practice 1st to say you could have measles so that staff can take precautions to avoid spreading the disease to others." Dr McCall said about 30 per cent of adult measles cases require hospitalisation.

[Byline: Amy Remeikis]

